rring status for the first 13 episodes of season 1, before joining the main cast in episode 14 of season 1.}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[List of 90210 characters#Ryan Matthews|Ryan Matthews]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ryan Eggold]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CNone}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[List of 90210 characters#Debbie Wilson|Debbie Wilson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lori Loughlin]]\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CMain}}\n| {{CNone}}\n| {{CGuest}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[List of 90210 characters#Liam Court|Liam Court]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Matt Lanter]]\n| {{CRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{CMain}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Teddy Montgomery (90210)|Teddy Montgomery]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Trevor Donovan]]\n| {{CNone}}\n| {{CRecurring}}\n| {{CMain}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[List of 90210 characters#Ivy Sullivan|Ivy Sullivan]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Gillian Zinser]]\n| {{CNone}}\n| {{CRecurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CMain}}\n| {{CNone}}\n|}\n\n;Notes:\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===Characters===\n{{Main|List of 90210 characters}}\nThe first actor to be cast was [[Dustin Milligan]] on April 1, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/04012008/tv/90210_has_its_dylan_104450.htm |title=''90210'' has its Dylan |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |author=Starr, Michael |date=April 1, 2008 |work=[[New York Post]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202023127/http://www.nypost.com/seven/04012008/tv/90210_has_its_dylan_104450.htm |archivedate=February 2, 2009 }}</ref> followed by [[AnnaLynne McCord]] on April 14.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/anna-lynne-mccord-joins-cast-of-new-90210_article_9112? |title=Anna Lynne McCord Joins Cast Of New ''90210'' |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |date=April 14, 2008|work=[[Access Hollywood]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202135429/http://www.accesshollywood.com/anna-lynne-mccord-joins-cast-of-new-90210_article_9112| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Sachs found Milligan to be \"really funny\", and changed Ethan to better represent his personality. McCord was cast because, according to Sachs, \"she's someone who is worldly, and there's a sophistication to her that's interesting\".<ref name=\"allcasting\" /> The role of Annie was given to [[Shenae Grimes]], who says she was raised watching the original series.<ref name=\"tvguidepilot\"/> Sachs and Judah had seen Grimes' work before and knew \"she had the acting chops\", and she was cast after acting a dramatic scene which she \"just killed\". Sachs stated, \"she can act, she's beautiful, and she can give this sweet cuteness [that lets us see] through her eyes into this world.\"<ref name=\"allcasting\" />\n\n[[Lori Loughlin]] auditioned for the role of Debbie and was given the part straight away. Sachs thought that Loughlin was too established to read for the part, but realized that she understood the role immediately. The producers were fans of [[Jessica Walter]] after watching her film, ''[[Play Misty for Me]]''. Sachs found that Walter knew pieces of scenes, and suggested \"stuff that works\".<ref name=\"allcasting\" /> Sachs described [[Ryan Eggold]], who portrayed Matthews, as \"a sophisticated actor, and he's also very funny\". Sachs believed that every time Eggold would be on screen, \"people are going to go, 'Wow!'\".<ref name=\"allcasting\" /> The producers were looking for an actor who could portray Silver as a \"quirky kid who moves to her own beat\". Sachs explained that [[Jessica Stroup]] \"came in dressed for the part, artsy and quirky, and she had her hair up and she had a bandanna. She nailed it.\"<ref name=\"allcasting\" /> The producers were fans of [[Tristan Wilds]] for his acting on ''[[The Wire]]'', and hoped to hire him as Dixon from the start of casting. When asked about [[Michael Steger]], who portrays Navid, Sachs said \"he's just great\".<ref name=\"allcasting\" /> [[Rob Estes]], the last actor to join the series, was a previous cast member of the first ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' spin-off, ''[[Melrose Place]]''. Estes was sought by The CW to play Harry,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/90210-Casting-Complete-11131.aspx |title=''90210'' Casting Complete: Rob Estes Heads for Hills |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |author=Mitovich, Matt |date=May 16, 2008 |work=[[TV Guide (magazine)|TV Guide]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202024826/http://www.tvguide.com/news/90210-Casting-Complete-11131.aspx| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> but was contracted on the drama ''[[Women's Murder Club (TV series)|Women's Murder Club]]''. When that series was cancelled, Sachs called Estes and explained the spin-off to him, and he thought it was a great idea. Sachs promised that although he was playing a parent, he would not \"be furniture... as in the seldom seen or heard parents who populate many youth-centric series, like the [[Characters of Beverly Hills, 90210#Supporting characters|Walsh parents]] on the original ''90210''.\"<ref name=\"allcasting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2008-07-31-90210-side_N.htm |title=Flip through West Beverly Hills' yearbook and get to know ''90210'' cast |accessdate=February 7, 2009 |author=Keveney, Bill |date=July 31, 2008 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nThe CW confirmed that [[Jennie Garth]], [[Shannen Doherty]], [[Tori Spelling]] and [[Joe E. Tata]] would be returning in recurring roles as their original characters.<ref name=\"oldiesback\">{{cite web |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08203/898326-67.stm |title=Tuned In: Doherty back as Brenda in ''90210'' |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |author=Owen, Rob |date=July 21, 2008 |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090203053027/http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08203/898326-67.stm?cmpid=radiotv.xml| archivedate=February 3, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Sachs was familiar with Garth, and talked to her about a possible role in the series. Garth agreed to star on the series without reading a script after brainstorming ideas with Sachs.<ref>Itzkoff, Dave (August 31, 2008). [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/31/arts/television/31sach.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print \"Gabe Sachs, executive producer, 90210\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved August 1, 2010.</ref> The producers offered Garth a role as a series regular, but she opted to sign on as a recurring character.<ref name=\"morecasting\"/> Doherty decided to appear after talking with Sachs, but her appearance was moved to the second episode.<ref name=\"oldiesback\" /> Sachs described Tata's casting as an accident; a friend told Sachs that he had seen Tata in a store, which led to the offer of a recurring role in the series. Sachs said that Tata was ecstatic about the idea and agreed.<ref name=\"tatacast2\" /> After reading the script, Spelling expressed interest in returning, and the writers decided to give her character her own fashion line.<ref name=\"tatacast2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-bevhills16-2008jul16-story.html |title=''90210'' on redial |author=Fernandez, Maria Elena |date=July 16, 2008 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160911101555/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-bevhills16-2008jul16-story.html |archivedate=September 11, 2016 |url-status=live |accessdate=September 11, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref> Spelling was scheduled to appear in the premi\u00e8re, but due to personal reasons and the birth of her daughter, she opted to appear later in the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4434_exclusive_tori_out_shannen_in_90210.html |title=Exclusive: Tori Is Out, Shannen Is In for ''90210'' Remake! |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |author=Dos Santos, Kristin |authorlink=Kristin Dos Santos |date=July 2, 2008 |website=[[E!]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202114301/http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4434_exclusive_tori_out_shannen_in_90210.html| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Conception===\nOnce pitched, the [[List of old television series that were returned to after years|project]] was put on the fast track by [[The CW]], and an order of the pilot was expected by the end of the month. The ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'' creator, [[Darren Star]], was announced not to be involved with the project. The only surviving element from the original series was believed to be [[Creative Artists Agency]], the talent agency which conceived the spin-off idea. ''[[Veronica Mars]]'' creator [[Rob Thomas (writer)|Rob Thomas]] was in negotiations to write the pilot and [[Mark Piznarski]] was in talks to direct it.\n\n===Development===\nA detailed breakdown of the pilot written by Thomas was released on March 17, 2008, containing information on the plot and characters which would be in the series. None of the characters were related to the original series of ''90210'' which again aired a few years before except Erin Silver played by Jessica Stroup; however, the new series' featured a similar premise: a family with two teenagers who recently moved from the Midwest to Beverly Hills. To reflect the situation at the Beverly Hills school, where around 40 percent of the students were of Persian descent, a student named Navid Shirazi was created. Thomas intended to introduce The Peach Pit, the diner from ''Beverly Hills, 90210'', but noted that it would not be featured in the pilot. The writer considered giving the siblings a job at a movie theater, as he did not want them to use their parents' credit cards. Thomas revealed that there were plans to reintroduce one of the original cast members, but had not met with any of them to discuss a role. Thomas later elaborated the producers wanted to see \"as many of the original cast members as possible\", but were careful not to \"parade them all out in the pilot\".\n\nOn April 14, 2008, Thomas announced that he was sidelining the series to focus on his two pilots for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. Gabe Sachs and Jeff Judah were hired as the new executive producers and wrote a new version of the script in late April. Sachs said that although Thomas had a \"great script\", their version of the script was edgier. Judah said that they were trying to ground their script in reality, with real character stories and emotional stories. The writers wanted the audience to relate to the characters' problems, which they wanted to be truthful and emotional, but also comedic. The pair were interested in telling several stories simultaneously, featuring many characters.<ref name=\"sachsinter\" /> The pair changed the surname of the main family from Mills to Wilson, along with changing the name of the mother from Celia to Debbie. The pair also told reporters that they would be adding their \"comedic impulses\" to the script.<ref name=\"tvguidepilot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/Fall-TV-Press-12658.aspx|title=Fall TV Press Tour: More ''90210'' Deets|accessdate=January 28, 2009|date=July 19, 2008|work=[[TV Guide (magazine)|TV Guide]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202094948/http://www.tvguide.com/news/Fall-TV-Press-12658.aspx| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Sachs and Judah found the parents to be an important part of the series, and designed to be contemporary parents.<ref name=\"sachsinter\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/31/arts/television/31sach.html?pagewanted=print|title=Gabe Sachs, executive producer, ''90210''|accessdate=January 28, 2009|author=Itzkoff, Dave|date=August 31, 2008|work=The New York Times| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141006095712/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/31/arts/television/31sach.html?pagewanted=print| archivedate=October 6, 2014| url-status= live}}</ref> Since the producers were both fathers, they designed the script to include more prominent adult story lines and a strong point of view on parenting. Judah was interested in focusing on how the family kept their moral center when moving to Beverly Hills, and the way the parents dealt with their teenagers.<ref name=\"writingscriptinfo\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08244/907778-67.stm|title=TV preview: ''90210''h, here we go again|accessdate=January 30, 2009|author=Owen, Rob|date=August 31, 2008|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202181347/http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08244/907778-67.stm| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> On May 11, 2008, one day before The CW's upfront presentations, the network officially picked up the series for the 2008\u20132009 television season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/topic/zap-cwupfront90210stylistabuzz,0,2145842.story|title=CW Picks up ''90210'', Tyra Banks' ''Stylista''|accessdate=January 30, 2009|date=May 12, 2008|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]}}</ref>\n\nDespite the first season having the highest ratings of the entire series run, the show was largely considered unsuccessful during its first season.  The characters were a hit. After disagreeing with the network executives over the series' storylines, Sachs and Judah ended their tenure as producers. The CW wanted the series to have a female perspective and focus more on teenage life and glamour; however, Judah and Sachs were more comfortable writing for men, featuring family stories. The studio brought in [[Rebecca Rand Kirshner Sinclair]], co-executive producer of the popular show ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'', to revamp the failing ''90210''. Sinclair is largely credited for saving the show, which had steady ratings in its third season. For the remainder of the first season, Judah worked in post-production, including editing and music supervision, while Sachs ran the production on set. [[Rebecca Rand Kirshner|Rebecca Sinclair]] began retooling the series as head writer and formally took over the show at the start of season 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashuatelegraph.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090203/ENCORE13/302039968/-1/OPINION02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517131713/http://www.nashuatelegraph.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20090203%2FENCORE13%2F302039968%2F-1%2FOPINION02 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 17, 2009 |title='90210' gets off to a rough start |accessdate=February 3, 2009 |date=February 3, 2009 |work=EncoreBuzz }}</ref> In late February 2009, Sinclair signed a seven-figure deal with the producers to serve as executive producer/showrunner for the series' second and third seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ib4ab512be78d9709c9bfd220114e2a23 |title=The Hollywood Reporter |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 27, 2009 |accessdate=September 12, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302095434/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ib4ab512be78d9709c9bfd220114e2a23 |archivedate=March 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2010, The CW renewed the show for a third season.<ref>[http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/02/the-cw-renews-top-model-vampire-diaries-supernatural-gossip-girl-90210.html The CW Renews \"Top Model\", \"Vampire Diaries\", \"Supernatural\", \"Gossip Girl\", \"90210\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/670fs7NlN?url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/02/the-cw-renews-top-model-vampire-diaries-supernatural-gossip-girl-90210.html |date=April 18, 2012 }}, ''Zap2It.com'', February 16, 2010.</ref> It was also moved to Mondays at 8/7c.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/CWs-Fall-Schedule-1020088.aspx|title=Top Model, Hellcats to Kick off CW's New Season|website=TVGuide.com}}</ref> On April 26, 2011, The CW renewed the show for a fourth season.<ref name=\"EarlyRenewals TheCW 2011-12\">{{cite web |url= https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/1/the-vampire-diaries-gossip-girl-90210-supernatural-americas-next-top-model-renewed-by-the-cw/|title=\"The Vampire Diaries,\" \"Gossip Girl,\" \"90210,\" \"Supernatural\" & \"America's Next Top Model\" Renewed By The CW |last=Gorman |first=Bill |date=April 26, 2011 |work=TV by the Numbers |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> On March 17, 2011, it was revealed that Sinclair would step down as executive producer when her contract expires at the end of season 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/90210-showrunner-rebecca-sinclair-leaving/|title=Exclusive: 90210 Showrunner Steps Down|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=April 17, 2011|work=TV Line|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> It was later announced that former ''[[Life Unexpected]]'' executive producers Patti Carr and Lara Olsen had been hired to take over the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/05/12/90210-life-unexpected-showrunners/|title='90210' hires 'Life Unexpected' showrunners|last=Ram|first=Archana|date=May 12, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=November 21, 2019| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525095054/http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/05/12/90210-life-unexpected-showrunners/| archivedate=May 25, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> The show also returned to its debut timeslot, Tuesday's at 8:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"schedule\">{{cite web|author=Matt Webb Mitovich |url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/05/fall-tv-preview-cw-schedule/ |title=The CW's Fall Schedule: Sarah Michelle Gellar Back on Tuesdays, Nikita Makes Move |website=TVLine.com |date=May 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 25, 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110608142922/http://www.tvline.com/2011/05/fall-tv-preview-cw-schedule/| archivedate=June 8, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> On May 3, 2012, The CW officially renewed ''90210'' for a fifth season.<ref>{{cite web|title=The CW Renews 'The Vampire Diaries,' '90210' and 'Supernatural'|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/03/the-cw-renews-the-vampire-diaries-90210-and-supernatural/132338/|date=May 3, 2012 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDVR ratings for the series have sometimes doubled its broadcast ratings.\n\nOn January 13, 2013, CW president [[Mark Pedowitz]] stated that though the show hadn't had a season 6 renewal in place, the show would most likely be back the following year for what would\u2019ve been its final season as he said he was a \"big believer in giving fans a very satisfactory conclusion\" for a long-running show. However, on February 28, 2013 the announcement came that the fifth season would be its last.\n\n===Casting===\nOn March 13, 2008, [[Kristin Dos Santos]] of [[E!]] confirmed that the series would be a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] with new characters and not a remake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4179_90210_hell_yes_series_spinoffled_by.html|title=''90210'' Hell, Yes: Series Spinoff...Led by ''Mars'' Boss Rob Thomas?! |accessdate=January 28, 2009|website=Eonline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202113524/http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4179_90210_hell_yes_series_spinoffled_by.html| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In order for the project to be ready for the network's \"upfront\" presentations to advertisers in May, casting began before the script was completed.<ref name=\"cwcasting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/23708147|title=First look at ''90210'' spinoff hints at family ties|accessdate=January 28, 2009|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n====Recurring====\nOriginal series actors [[Shannen Doherty]], [[Jennie Garth]] and [[Joe E. Tata]] signed on for recurring roles during early production.<ref name=\"oldiesback\"/> Sachs was familiar with Garth, and talked to her about a possible role in the series. Garth agreed to work in the series without reading a script after brainstorming ideas with Sachs.<ref name=\"sachsinter\" /> Initially, the producers offered Garth a role as a series regular but, she opted to sign on as recurring instead.<ref name=\"morecasting\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4357_90210_Reunion_Tori_Spelling_to_Guest_in_Pilot_Ian_Ziering_Definitely_Wants_In.html \n |title=''90210'' Reunion: Tori Spelling to Guest in Pilot; Ian Ziering Definitely Wants In \n |website=Eonline.com \n |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121216055105/http://www.eonline.com/news/4357/90210-reunion-tori-spelling-to-guest-in-pilot-ian-ziering-definitely-wants-in \n |archivedate=December 16, 2012 \n |url-status=live \n |accessdate=September 11, 2016 \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref>\nSachs met with Doherty over dinner, and told her about the ''90210'' spin-off. Over the next few weeks, they established Brenda's backstory as a 'name' stage actress and Doherty agreed to guest-star in several episodes,<ref name=\"sachsinter\" /><ref name=\"oldiesback\" /> appearing in the credits during the first half-season. Otherwise, Doherty only appeared in supporting roles.\n\nFrom early on in the news reports of the upcoming series through most of the summer, it was reported that along with Doherty and Garth, Tori Spelling would be reprising her role as an older alumni of West Beverly Hills High. After reading the script, [[Tori Spelling]] expressed interest returning, and the writers decided to give Donna her own fashion line.<ref>{{Cite news\n |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/photos/la-et-bevhills16-2008jul16,0,7739205.story \n |title=''90210'' on redial \n |work=Los Angeles Times \n |date=July 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517202326/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/photos/la-et-bevhills16-2008jul16%2C0%2C7739205.story \n |archivedate=May 17, 2009 \n |url-status=live \n |accessdate=September 11, 2016 \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref> Spelling was scheduled to appear in the premiere, but due to personal reasons and the birth of her daughter, she opted to appear later in the season.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4434_exclusive_tori_out_shannen_in_90210.html \n |title=Exclusive: Tori Is Out, Shannen Is In for ''90210'' Remake! \n |author=Dos Santos, Kristin \n |authorlink=Kristin Dos Santos \n |date=July 2, 2008 \n |website=[[E!]] \n |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120730211654/http://uk.eonline.com/news/4434/exclusive-tori-is-out-shannen-is-in-for-90210-remake \n |archivedate=July 30, 2012 \n |url-status=live \n |accessdate=September 11, 2016 \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref> Backdrop retail store signage in the first several episodes during shopping excursions scenes and one setup line referring to her role foreshadowed the role that would be unfulfilled. By August 11, it was reported that Spelling had pulled out of the series after discovering that she was receiving less pay than Garth and Doherty. Spelling asked for her salary of $20,000 per episode to be increased to match their salaries\u2014$40,000 to $50,000 per episode\u2014but when denied she left the show altogether.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b23176_sources_confirm_tori_pulls_out_of_90210.html|title=Sources Confirm: Tori Pulls Out of ''90210'' Spinoff|accessdate=January 29, 2009|website=Eonline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202040138/http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b23176_sources_confirm_tori_pulls_out_of_90210.html| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n====Regulars====\nThe first actor to be cast was [[Dustin Milligan]] as lacrosse player Ethan Ward,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/04012008/tv/90210_has_its_dylan_104450.htm |title=''90210'' has its Dylan |accessdate=January 29, 2009 |author=Starr, Michael |date=April 1, 2008 |work=New York Post |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202023127/http://www.nypost.com/seven/04012008/tv/90210_has_its_dylan_104450.htm |archivedate=February 2, 2009 }}</ref> followed by [[AnnaLynne McCord]] as [[Naomi Clark]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/anna-lynne-mccord-joins-cast-of-new-90210_article_9112?\n |title=Anna Lynne McCord Joins Cast Of New ''90210''|accessdate=January 29, 2009|date=April 14, 2008\n|website=Access Hollywood.com\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202135429/http://www.accesshollywood.com/anna-lynne-mccord-joins-cast-of-new-90210_article_9112| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> The role of aspiring actress Annie Wilson, won by [[Shenae Grimes]], was originally offered to [[Hilary Duff]], who turned it down due to dissatisfaction with the pilot script.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/watch_with_kristin/b4286_hilary_duff_not_bound_90210.html\n |title= Hilary Duff not bound for 90210|accessdate=April 20, 2012|author=Kristin Dos Santos|date=December 13, 2009|website=E! Online}}</ref><ref name=\"tvguidepilot\" />\n\n[[Jessica Lowndes]] was selected to portray actress and singer Adrianna Tate-Duncan, introduced as a theater performer who suffered through a drug addiction,<ref \n name=\"Thefutoncritic.com\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/rant.aspx?id=20080620\n |title=The Futon's First Look: The CW's \"90210\" (Plus ABC's \"Making It Legal\")|work=Thefutoncritic.com|accessdate=June 20, 2008}}</ref> and would also go through a teen pregnancy and many other serious conflicts as a dark character with many lovable aspects. The Adrianna Tate-Duncan role had been upgraded to a starring role in Jessica Walters' spot,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2008/10/15/jessica-walter/|title=9021-Oh No They Didn't: Jessica Walter Taken Off Contract |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67ojQhTVj?url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2008/10/jessica-walter.html |archivedate=May 21, 2012|df=mdy }}</ref> [[Tristan Wilds]] was cast as step-brother to Annie Wilson; [[Lori Loughlin]] won the role of their mother, photographer wife Debbie Wilson. [[Michael Steger]] was cast as the school television news director and congenial very nice guy, Navid Shirazi who maintained the nice-guy status throughout all 114 episodes (2008-2013) of generally being walked on or victimized.\n \n[[Rob Estes]] was the last actor to join the series; he was sought by The CW to play the part of Harry Wilson, and would only appear in the first two seasons. Estes was a previous cast member of the first ''Beverly Hills, 90210'' spin-off, ''[[Melrose Place]]''.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/90210-Casting-Complete-11131.aspx\n |title=''90210'' Casting Complete: Rob Estes Heads for Hills\n |accessdate=January 29, 2009|last=Mitovich|first=Matt|date=May 16, 2008|work=TV Guide.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090202024826/http://www.tvguide.com/news/90210-Casting-Complete-11131.aspx| archivedate=February 2, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===New direction===\nSinclair announced in March 2009 that the series' second season would rely less on ''90210'' alums like Jennie Garth and Shannen Doherty to boost ratings. She felt that \"the show tried to be a lot of things to a lot of people in its first season [...] I think the center lies with the generation of kids that are in high school now.\" It was also announced that Dustin Milligan ('Ethan Ward') would not be coming back for season two, while [[Matt Lanter]] would be joining the cast as a series regular.<ref name=\"mil\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/03/30/exclusive-90210/|title=''90210'' shocker: Leading man Milligan to exit |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=September 12, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807222957/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/03/30/exclusive-90210/ |archivedate=August 7, 2009 }}</ref> Casting soon began for new characters to be introduced in the second season. In June 2009, the series was reportedly looking for an actor to play the recurring role of Teddy, a tennis champ returning to West Beverly.<ref name=\"td\">{{cite web |url= https://www.tvguide.com/news/90210-exclusive-ethan-1006542/|title=90210 Exclusive: Meet Ethan's Replacement|website=TVGuide.com |accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> Actor and model [[Trevor Donovan]] was later cast in the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2009/06/29/days-hunk-trevor-donovan-joins-90210/|title='90210' exclusive: 'Days' hunk Trevor Donovan cast as model citizen |website=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 29, 2009 |accessdate=November 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701031253/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/06/days-hunk-trevor-donovan-joins-90210.html |archivedate=July 1, 2009 }}</ref> Ann Gillespie returned in the second season for multiple episodes as Jackie Taylor, Silver and Kelly's mother. Her character was once again sober and hoped to reconnect with her daughters after being diagnosed with cancer.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite web|url= https://ew.com/article/2009/08/03/this-just-in-another-90210-vet-returns-again/ |title=This just in: Another '90210' vet returns (again)!|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=August 3, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806010536/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/08/03/this-just-in-another-90210-vet-returns-again/ |archivedate=August 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOne of the show's locations was a complex on Waverly Drive in the [[Los Feliz]] neighborhood, designed by architect [[Bernard Maybeck]] in 1927 and best known as the [[convent]] of [[Sisters of the Immaculate Heart of Mary|Immaculate Heart of Mary]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Katy Perry, 5 Nuns And 1 Hipster Neighborhood|last=Bascher|first=Danielle|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 31, 2015|volume=127|issue=32|pages=42\u201345}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\n''90210'' first aired in the United States on [[The CW]], Tuesdays at 8:00 pm [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]/7:00 pm [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central]].<ref name=\"schedule\" />\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the series airs on [[Channel 4]] and [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]], after beating off competition from [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]], [[ITV2]] and [[Living (UK TV channel)|Living]] for the rights to broadcast the show. In November 2018, 90210 was made available on Channel 4's [[All 4]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/27/90210-channel-4 90210 on Channel 4]. Retrieved: October 1, 2010.</ref> In Australia, it aired on [[Network Ten]] for 6 episodes until the network pulled it from their schedules due to low ratings. However, in January 2011 it started airing on [[Eleven (TV channel)|Eleven]] as part of a broadcast schedule aimed at a younger audience.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/ten-launches-channel-eleven-20100826-13spf.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |title=Ten launches channel Eleven |first=Michael |last=Idato |date=August 26, 2010}}</ref> Due to poor performance, [[Eleven (TV channel)|Eleven]] also pulled ''90210'' off their schedule. It's now shown on Sunday Afternoons at 5:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2011/01/gone-90210-bumped-so-you-think-you-can-dance.html |work=TV Tonight |title=Gone: 90210 |date=January 28, 2011}}</ref> The show airs in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] on [[RT\u00c9 Two]], initially the show aired in a prime-time slot of Thursdays paired with ''[[Ugly Betty]]''. When the show returned for its second season the show was moved to an early morning timeslot of just after midnight where it still airs. In [[India]], it airs on Big CBS Channels.\n\n90210 went on its mid-season break on December 10, 2012, and is scheduled to return on January 21, 2013, at a new time slot of 9:00&nbsp;pm, one week after the premiere of ''The Carrie Diaries'', which took its original time slot of 8:00&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2012/11/08/carrie-diaries-date/|title='Carrie Diaries' gets CW premiere date|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 8, 2012|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Digital video recorder|DVR]] ratings for the series have sometimes doubled its broadcast ratings.<ref name=\"DVR Dawn\" /><ref name=\"DVR 90210\" />\n\nOn January 13, 2013, CW president [[Mark Pedowitz]] stated that though the show hadn't had a season 6 renewal in place, the show would most likely be back the following year for what would\u2019ve been its final season as he said he was a \"big believer in giving fans a very satisfactory conclusion\" for a long-running show. <ref name=\"tvline.com\">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2013/01/13/supernatural-season-9-renewal-cw|title=CW Boss Talks Wonder Woman, 'Vampire Diaries' Spin-Off, 'Supernatural' Renewal and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|work=TV Linedate=January 13, 2013|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> However, on February 28, 2013 the announcement came that the fifth season would be its last.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=CW\u2019s \u201890210\u2019 Cancelled After Five Seasons |url=https://deadline.com/2013/02/90210-cancelled-after-season-cw-443058/ |website=Deadline |accessdate=November 21, 2019 |date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\nSeasonal rankings (based on average total viewers per episode) of ''90210'' on The CW.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! style=\"width:28%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Timeslot ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|ET]])\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| # Ep.\n! colspan=2| Premiered\n! colspan=2| Ended\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| TV Season\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Rank\n! style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Viewers<br />(in millions)\n! style=\"