{"title_page": "Sons of the Harpy", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n |title = Sons of the Harpy\n |image = \n |image_size = \n |caption = \n |series = [[Game of Thrones]]\n |season = 5\n |episode = 4\n |director = [[Mark Mylod]]\n |writer = [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]]\n |producer =\n |music = [[Ramin Djawadi]] \n |editor = [[Tim Porter]]\n |photographer = Anette Haellmigk\n |production = \n |airdate = {{Start date|2015|5|3}}\n |length = 50 minutes \n |guests =\n* [[Jonathan Pryce]] as High Sparrow\n* [[Ian McElhinney]] as Ser Barristan Selmy\n* [[Julian Glover]] as Grand Maester Pycelle\n* [[Anton Lesser]] as Qyburn\n* [[Tara Fitzgerald]] as Selyse Baratheon\n* [[Roger Ashton-Griffiths]] as Mace Tyrell\n* [[Jacob Anderson]] as Grey Worm\n* [[Ian Beattie]] as Ser Meryn Trant\n* [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] as Hizdahr zo Loraq\n* [[Eugene Simon]] as Lancel Lannister\n* [[Ben Crompton]] as Edd Tollett\n* [[Keisha Castle-Hughes]] as Obara Sand\n* [[Rosabell Laurenti Sellers]] as Tyene Sand\n* [[Jessica Henwick]] as Nymeria Sand\n* [[Kerry Ingram]] as Shireen Baratheon\n* [[Brenock O'Connor]] as Olly\n* [[Finn Jones]] as Loras Tyrell\n* [[Will Tudor]] as Olyvar\n* Josephine Gillan as Marei\n |season_list =\n |prev = [[High Sparrow (Game of Thrones)|High Sparrow]]\n |next = [[Kill the Boy]]\n |season_article = Game of Thrones (season 5)\n|episode_list = List of Game of Thrones episodes\n}}\n\"'''Sons of the Harpy'''\" is the fourth episode of the [[Game of Thrones (season 5)|fifth season]] of [[HBO]]'s [[fantasy]] television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', and the 44th overall. The episode was written by [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]], and directed by [[Mark Mylod]].<ref name=\"s5 directors\">{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/07/15/game-of-thrones-season-5-directors/ |title='Game of Thrones' season 5 directors chosen |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=July 15, 2014 |accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref> It aired on May 3, 2015.<ref name=\"futon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/game-of-thrones/listings/ |title=Shows A-Z - game of thrones on HBO |work=The Futon Critic |accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> Prior to airing, this episode was leaked online along with the first three episodes of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/12/technology/game-of-thrones-leaked-episodes/|title='Game of Thrones': First four episodes leaked before premiere|last=Goldman|first=David|publisher=CNN|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe episode received a nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series]] at the [[67th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/09/emmys-2015-creative-arts-winners-live-blog-1201523192/|title='Game of Thrones': 67th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|last=Haithman|first=Diane|publisher=Deadline|date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref> The episode was met with generally positive reviews, but received heavy criticism for the decision to kill off Ser Barristan Selmy, who in the novels is still alive and is a major supporting character.\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=May 2019}}<!--\"Too long\" means over 400 words per MOS:TVPLOT. Therefore do NOT remove tag until episode is under 400 words.-->\n\n===In King's Landing===\nMace informs Cersei that the Iron Bank has called in 10% of their debt and that they can pay only half that amount. Cersei sends Mace to Braavos with Meryn to negotiate a deal.\n\nCersei authorisizes the High Sparrow to revive the Faith Militant. The Militant arrests Loras because of his homosexuality. Margaery asks Tommen to order his release, but the Faith Militant prevent Tommen from disturbing him from prayer. Margaery informs Olenna of the situation.\n\n===At the Wall===\nJon signs several letters to be sent to northern lords, including Roose Bolton, asking them to send men for the Night's Watch. Melisandre asks Jon to join Stannis in taking Winterfell from the Boltons, but he declines.\n\n===At Winterfell===\nPetyr informs Sansa that he is leaving Winterfell to return to King's Landing at Cersei's request and that Stannis will soon take Winterfell from the Boltons and make Sansa Wardeness of the North.\n\n===In Dorne===\nJaime and Bronn arrive in Dorne. Jaime tells Bronn that he will kill Tyrion for murdering Tywin if he ever sees him again. Oberyn's bastard daughters Obara, Nymeria and Tyene, known as\u00a0the Sand Snakes agree to join Ellaria in starting a war against the Lannisters.\n\n===On the Summer Sea===\nJorah sets sail with captive Tyrion, who deduces Jorah's identity and learns that he is being taken to Daenerys.\n\n===In Meereen===\nHizdahr repeats his request to reopen the fighting pits. Several Unsullied, led by Grey Worm are attacked by the Sons of the Harpy. Barristan arrives to assist Grey Worm and after a battle, they collapse next to each other, surrounded by dead Unsullied and Sons of the Harpy.\n\n==Production==\n===Writing===\nThis episode was the first to be written by staff writer [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]], who previously worked as an assistant to showrunners [[David Benioff]] and [[D. B. Weiss]] and contains content from two of [[George R. R. Martin]]'s novels, ''[[A Feast for Crows]]'', Cersei IV and Cersei VI, and ''[[A Dance with Dragons]]'', chapters Tyrion VII, Jon II, with elements of Daenerys II and the Epilogue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/game-of-thrones-benioff-weiss-interview |title=The Surprising Connection Between ''Game of Thrones'' and ''Monty Python'' |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 24, 2014 |accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Westeros.org>{{cite web|url=http://www.westeros.org/GoT/Episodes/Entry/The_Sons_Of_The_Harpy/Book_Spoilers/#Analysis|title=EP504: THE SONS OF THE HARPY|last=Garcia|first=Elio|last2=Antonsson|first2=Linda|work=Westeros.org|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLike the season's earlier episodes, \"Sons of the Harpy\" deviated from George Martin's novels in several places. Hilary Busis and Darren Francich of ''Entertainment Weekly'' continued their approval of the decision to consolidate the Sansa and Arya impostor storylines. The scene between Stannis and Shireen was written specifically for the episode.<ref name=EntertainmentWeeklyBookClub>{{cite web|url= http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/game-of-thrones-tv-book-club-sons-of-the-harpy |title=Game of Thrones TV Book Club: Did 'Sons of the Harpy' just confirm a huge fan theory? |last=Busis|first=Hilary|last2=Francich|first2=Darren|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Both Sarah Moran of ''Screen Rant'' and Matt Fowler of ''IGN'' agreed that interacting with a more visible and vocal Shireen gives Stannis's character some emotional depth, with Moran adding that the change \"gives us insight into characters we already know.\"<ref name=IGN/><ref name=ScreenRant>{{cite web| title=\u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 Season 5 Episode 4: Book to Screen Spoiler Discussion|url=http://screenrant.com/game-thrones-season-5-episode-4-spoilers-deaths/|work=Screen Rant|last=Moran|first=Sarah|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMoran also approved of the streamlined story and cast, noting that the show has \"whittled down Oberyn Martell's bastard daughters from eight to three\" and giving Arianne Martell's plotline to the already-established Ellaria Sand.<ref name=ScreenRant /> David Crow of ''Den of Geek'' expressed reservations about the scene in which Grey Worm and Barristan Selmy are wounded and left for dead, referring to it as \"vainglorious and artificial,\" but he also said, \"Bringing Bronn back into the fold was one of ''Game of Thrones'' more astute changes from the books as he offers a great counterbalance to either Lannister brother.\"<ref name=DenofGeek>{{cite web|title=Game of Thrones: The Sons of the Harpy Review|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/game-of-thrones/245784/game-of-thrones-the-sons-of-the-harpy-review-selmy-barristan-cersei-lannister|work=Den of Geek|last=Crow|first=David|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Matt Fowler of IGN, however, found the acceleration of the Faith Militant storyline jarring, \"like a time-crunch collage.\"<ref name=IGN>{{cite web |title=Game of Thrones: \"Sons of the Harpy\" Review|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/04/game-of-thrones-sons-of-the-harpy-review|work=IGN|last=Fowler|first=Matt|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nThe episode has the introduction of new recurring cast members [[Keisha Castle-Hughes]], [[Jessica Henwick]] and [[Rosabell Laurenti Sellers]], who play the Sand Snakes: Obara, Nymeria and Tyene Sand.\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n\"Sons of the Harpy\" was watched by an estimated 6.82 million American viewers during its first airing, and received a 3.6 rating among adults 18\u201349.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/05/05/sunday-cable-ratings-game-of-thrones-tops-night-real-housewives-of-atlanta-silicon-valley-more/399327/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Game of Thrones' Tops Night + 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'Silicon Valley' & More|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the episode was viewed by 2.151 million viewers, making it the highest-rated broadcast that week. It also received 0.164 million timeshift viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10?|title=Top 10 Ratings (4-10 May 2015)|work=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board|BARB]]|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reviews===\n\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] scored this episode at 100% based on 30 reviews with an average score of 8.1 out of 10, stating \"An episode that benefits from the intricate plotting of the previous three, \"Sons of the Harpy\" balances bloody action with illuminating character interplay.\"<ref name=RottenTomatoes>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/game-of-thrones/s05/e04/?adid=Super_TVOB_GoT_Pos1 |title=Sons of the Harpy - Game of Thrones: Season 5, Episode 4 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavid Crow of ''Den of Geek'' called this the weakest episode of the season so far but still reasonably solid.<ref name=DenofGeek /> Eric Kain of ''Forbes'' writes, \"All told, an excellent episode filled with revelations and surprises, great action and fantastic drama. I\u2019m excited to see the back story begin to emerge in earnest, something I\u2019ve been wondering about for years.\"<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title='Game Of Thrones' Season 5, Episode 4 Review: Sons of the Harpy|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/05/03/game-of-thrones-season-5-episode-4-review-sons-of-the-harpy/|work=Forbes|last=Kain|first=Eric|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquotepar|Game_of_Thrones/Season_5#The_Sons_of_the_Harpy_.5B5.04.5D|Sons of the Harpy}}\n* {{URL|1=http://www.hbo.com/game-of-thrones/episodes/5/44-sons-of-the-harpy/index.html|2=\"Sons of the Harpy\"}} at [[HBO.com]]\n* {{IMDb episode|3866838|Sons of the Harpy}}\n* {{tv.com episode|game-of-thrones/sons-of-the-harpy-3075166/|Sons of the Harpy}}\n\n{{Game of Thrones episodes|5}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sons of the Harpy}}\n[[Category:2015 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Game of Thrones (season 5) episodes]]\n[[Category:Homophobia in fiction]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about prejudice against LGBT people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n |title = Sons of the Harpy\n |image = \n |image_size = \n |caption = \n |series = [[Game of Thrones]]\n |season = 5\n |episode = 4\n |director = [[Mark Mylod]]\n |writer = [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]]\n |producer =\n |music = [[Ramin Djawadi]] \n |editor = [[Tim Porter]]\n |photographer = Anette Haellmigk\n |production = \n |airdate = {{Start date|2015|5|3}}\n |length = 50 minutes \n |guests =\n* [[Jonathan Pryce]] as High Sparrow\n* [[Ian McElhinney]] as Ser Barristan Selmy\n* [[Julian Glover]] as Grand Maester Pycelle\n* [[Anton Lesser]] as Qyburn\n* [[Tara Fitzgerald]] as Selyse Baratheon\n* [[Roger Ashton-Griffiths]] as Mace Tyrell\n* [[Jacob Anderson]] as Grey Worm\n* [[Ian Beattie]] as Ser Meryn Trant\n* [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] as Hizdahr zo Loraq\n* [[Eugene Simon]] as Lancel Lannister\n* [[Ben Crompton]] as Edd Tollett\n* [[Keisha Castle-Hughes]] as Obara Sand\n* [[Rosabell Laurenti Sellers]] as Tyene Sand\n* [[Jessica Henwick]] as Nymeria Sand\n* [[Kerry Ingram]] as Shireen Baratheon\n* [[Brenock O'Connor]] as Olly\n* [[Finn Jones]] as Loras Tyrell\n* [[Will Tudor]] as Olyvar\n* Josephine Gillan as Marei\n |season_list =\n |prev = [[High Sparrow (Game of Thrones)|High Sparrow]]\n |next = [[Kill the Boy]]\n |season_article = Game of Thrones (season 5)\n|episode_list = List of Game of Thrones episodes\n}}\n\"'''Sons of the Harpy'''\" is the fourth episode of the [[Game of Thrones (season 5)|fifth season]] of [[HBO]]'s [[fantasy]] television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', and the 44th overall. The episode was written by [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]], and directed by [[Mark Mylod]].<ref name=\"s5 directors\">{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/07/15/game-of-thrones-season-5-directors/ |title='Game of Thrones' season 5 directors chosen |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=July 15, 2014 |accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref> It aired on May 3, 2015.<ref name=\"futon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/game-of-thrones/listings/ |title=Shows A-Z - game of thrones on HBO |work=The Futon Critic |accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> Prior to airing, this episode was leaked online along with the first three episodes of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/12/technology/game-of-thrones-leaked-episodes/|title='Game of Thrones': First four episodes leaked before premiere|last=Goldman|first=David|publisher=CNN|date=April 12, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe episode received a nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series]] at the [[67th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/09/emmys-2015-creative-arts-winners-live-blog-1201523192/|title='Game of Thrones': 67th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|last=Haithman|first=Diane|publisher=Deadline|date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref> The episode was met with generally positive reviews, but received heavy criticism for the decision to kill off Ser Barristan Selmy, who in the novels is still alive and is a major supporting character.\n\n==Plot==\n{{long plot|date=May 2019}}<!--\"Too long\" means over 400 words per MOS:TVPLOT. Therefore do NOT remove tag until episode is under 400 words.-->\n\n===In King's Landing===\nMace informs Cersei that the Iron Bank has called in 10% of their debt and that they can pay only half that amount. Cersei sends Mace to Braavos with Meryn to negotiate a deal.\n\nCersei authorisizes the High Sparrow to revive the Faith Militant. The Militant arrests Loras because of his homosexuality. Margaery asks Tommen to order his release, but the Faith Militant prevent Tommen from disturbing him from prayer. Margaery informs Olenna of the situation.\n\n===At the Wall===\nJon signs several letters to be sent to northern lords, including Roose Bolton, asking them to send men for the Night's Watch. Melisandre asks Jon to join Stannis in taking Winterfell from the Boltons, but he declines.\n\n===At Winterfell===\nPetyr informs Sansa that he is leaving Winterfell to return to King's Landing at Cersei's request and that Stannis will soon take Winterfell from the Boltons and make Sansa Wardeness of the North.\n\n===In Dorne===\nJaime and Bronn arrive in Dorne. Jaime tells Bronn that he will kill Tyrion for murdering Tywin if he ever sees him again. Oberyn's bastard daughters Obara, Nymeria and Tyene, known as\u00a0the Sand Snakes agree to join Ellaria in starting a war against the Lannisters.\n\n===On the Summer Sea===\nJorah sets sail with captive Tyrion, who deduces Jorah's identity and learns that he is being taken to Daenerys.\n\n===In Meereen===\nHizdahr repeats his request to reopen the fighting pits. Several Unsullied, led by Grey Worm are attacked by the Sons of the Harpy. Barristan arrives to assist Grey Worm and after a battle, they collapse next to each other, surrounded by dead Unsullied and Sons of the Harpy.\n\n==Production==\n===Writing===\nThis episode was the first to be written by staff writer [[Dave Hill (screenwriter)|Dave Hill]], who previously worked as an assistant to showrunners [[David Benioff]] and [[D. B. Weiss]] and contains content from two of [[George R. R. Martin]]'s novels, ''[[A Feast for Crows]]'', Cersei IV and Cersei VI, and ''[[A Dance with Dragons]]'', chapters Tyrion VII, Jon II, with elements of Daenerys II and the Epilogue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/game-of-thrones-benioff-weiss-interview |title=The Surprising Connection Between ''Game of Thrones'' and ''Monty Python'' |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 24, 2014 |accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Westeros.org>{{cite web|url=http://www.westeros.org/GoT/Episodes/Entry/The_Sons_Of_The_Harpy/Book_Spoilers/#Analysis|title=EP504: THE SONS OF THE HARPY|last=Garcia|first=Elio|last2=Antonsson|first2=Linda|work=Westeros.org|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLike the season's earlier episodes, \"Sons of the Harpy\" deviated from George Martin's novels in several places. Hilary Busis and Darren Francich of ''Entertainment Weekly'' continued their approval of the decision to consolidate the Sansa and Arya impostor storylines. The scene between Stannis and Shireen was written specifically for the episode.<ref name=EntertainmentWeeklyBookClub>{{cite web|url= http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/04/game-of-thrones-tv-book-club-sons-of-the-harpy |title=Game of Thrones TV Book Club: Did 'Sons of the Harpy' just confirm a huge fan theory? |last=Busis|first=Hilary|last2=Francich|first2=Darren|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Both Sarah Moran of ''Screen Rant'' and Matt Fowler of ''IGN'' agreed that interacting with a more visible and vocal Shireen gives Stannis's character some emotional depth, with Moran adding that the change \"gives us insight into characters we already know.\"<ref name=IGN/><ref name=ScreenRant>{{cite web| title=\u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 Season 5 Episode 4: Book to Screen Spoiler Discussion|url=http://screenrant.com/game-thrones-season-5-episode-4-spoilers-deaths/|work=Screen Rant|last=Moran|first=Sarah|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMoran also approved of the streamlined story and cast, noting that the show has \"whittled down Oberyn Martell's bastard daughters from eight to three\" and giving Arianne Martell's plotline to the already-established Ellaria Sand.<ref name=ScreenRant /> David Crow of ''Den of Geek'' expressed reservations about the scene in which Grey Worm and Barristan Selmy are wounded and left for dead, referring to it as \"vainglorious and artificial,\" but he also said, \"Bringing Bronn back into the fold was one of ''Game of Thrones'' more astute changes from the books as he offers a great counterbalance to either Lannister brother.\"<ref name=DenofGeek>{{cite web|title=Game of Thrones: The Sons of the Harpy Review|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/game-of-thrones/245784/game-of-thrones-the-sons-of-the-harpy-review-selmy-barristan-cersei-lannister|work=Den of Geek|last=Crow|first=David|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref> Matt Fowler of IGN, however, found the acceleration of the Faith Militant storyline jarring, \"like a time-crunch collage.\"<ref name=IGN>{{cite web |title=Game of Thrones: \"Sons of the Harpy\" Review|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/04/game-of-thrones-sons-of-the-harpy-review|work=IGN|last=Fowler|first=Matt|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nThe episode has the introduction of new recurring cast members [[Keisha Castle-Hughes]], [[Jessica Henwick]] and [[Rosabell Laurenti Sellers]], who play the Sand Snakes: Obara, Nymeria and Tyene Sand.\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n\"Sons of the Harpy\" was watched by an estimated 6.82 million American viewers during its first airing, and received a 3.6 rating among adults 18-49.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/05/05/sunday-cable-ratings-game-of-thrones-tops-night-real-housewives-of-atlanta-silicon-valley-more/399327/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'Game of Thrones' Tops Night + 'Real Housewives of Atlanta', 'Silicon Valley' & More|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the episode was viewed by 2.151 million viewers, making it the highest-rated broadcast that week. It also received 0.164 million timeshift viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10?|title=Top 10 Ratings (4-10 May 2015)|work=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board|BARB]]|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reviews===\n\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] scored this episode at 100% based on 30 reviews with an average score of 8.1 out of 10, stating \"An episode that benefits from the intricate plotting of the previous three, \"Sons of the Harpy\" balances bloody action with illuminating character interplay.\"<ref name=RottenTomatoes>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/game-of-thrones/s05/e04/?adid=Super_TVOB_GoT_Pos1 |title=Sons of the Harpy - Game of Thrones: Season 5, Episode 4 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavid Crow of ''Den of Geek'' called this the weakest episode of the season so far but still reasonably solid.<ref name=DenofGeek /> Eric Kain of ''Forbes'' writes, \"All told, an excellent episode filled with revelations and surprises, great action and fantastic drama. I\u2019m excited to see the back story begin to emerge in earnest, something I\u2019ve been wondering about for years.\"<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title='Game Of Thrones' Season 5, Episode 4 Review: Sons of the Harpy|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/05/03/game-of-thrones-season-5-episode-4-review-sons-of-the-harpy/|work=Forbes|last=Kain|first=Eric|date=May 3, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquotepar|Game_of_Thrones/Season_5#The_Sons_of_the_Harpy_.5B5.04.5D|Sons of the Harpy}}\n* {{URL|1=http://www.hbo.com/game-of-thrones/episodes/5/44-sons-of-the-harpy/index.html|2=\"Sons of the Harpy\"}} at [[HBO.com]]\n* {{IMDb episode|3866838|Sons of the Harpy}}\n* {{tv.com episode|game-of-thrones/sons-of-the-harpy-3075166/|Sons of the Harpy}}\n\n{{Game of Thrones episodes|5}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sons of the Harpy}}\n[[Category:2015 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Game of Thrones (season 5) episodes]]\n[[Category:Homophobia in fiction]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about prejudice against LGBT people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRatings:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 18-49 \u2192 18\u201349", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sons_of_the_Harpy"}
{"title_page": "Douglas Cardinal", "text_new": "{{Infobox architect\n|name                 = Douglas Cardinal\n|image                = Douglas Cardinal - 2016 (25010970829).jpg\n|caption              = Cardinal in 2016\n|nationality          = \n|birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1934|3|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place          = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n|death_date           = \n|death_place          = \n|alma_mater           =[[University of British Columbia]]; [[University of Texas at Austin]], \n|practice             = \n|significant_buildings= \n|significant_projects = [[National Museum of the American Indian]]; [[Grande Prairie Regional College]]; [[Canadian Museum of History]]; \n|significant_design   = \n|awards               = \n}}\n'''Douglas Joseph Cardinal''', [[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada|FRAIC]] (born 7 March 1934) is an [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Indigenous]] [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[architect]] based in [[Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada. His flowing architecture marked with smooth curvilinear forms is influenced by his [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] heritage as well as European [[Expressionist architecture]].<ref name=\"CE\">[http://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-joseph-cardinal/ Douglas Cardinal], The Canadian Encyclopedia</ref> His passion for unconventional forms and appreciation of nature and landscape were present in his life from a very young age, and consequently developed into the unique architectural style he has employed throughout his career. Cardinal is perhaps best known for his designs of the [[Canadian Museum of History]] in [[Gatineau, Quebec]] (1989) and the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] (1998).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=39}}</ref> He is considered one of the most influential Aboriginal architects, having shaped and preserved indigenous architecture and culture in modern history.\n\n==Life==\nBorn in [[Calgary, Alberta]] to parents Joseph and Frances Cardinal, Douglas Cardinal is the eldest of eight children. His father was of [[Blackfoot]]/Kainai and Algonquin heritage, and his mother was of German and [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] descent.<ref name=\"CE\"/> His mother worked as a nurse and was very well educated. Cardinal's parents met in 1926, and in the first half of the 20th century women had very little status and rights. The patriarchal society did not recognize educated women like Frances Cardinal. However, his father's tribe's societal norms accepted a matrilineal culture, where women are very respected and admired.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 2018|title=Douglas Cardinal|url=|journal=The Canadian Architect|volume= 63, Iss. 2|pages=30\u201332|via=}}</ref> These cultural ideas shaped Cardinal's upbringing and affected his worldview and relationship with his heritage. He has recalled that his mother told him at a young age, \u201cYou\u2019re going to be an architect.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n \nCardinal grew up in a small city in [[Red Deer, Alberta]]. He was sent to St. Joseph's Convent Catholic [[Canadian Indian residential school system|Residential School]] and spent the remainder of his high school years in Red Deer. [[Grey Nuns]] taught him about arts and culture, and he has said that his religious school influenced him immensely. Living away from the rest of his family made him focus on his academic achievements. Traditional sacred architecture and its role in culture made him want to create spaces as powerful and inspirational as churches and basilicas. It also ignited in him a passion for architecture in those early years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, Ontario|pages=14}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, he started studying architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) but was forced to leave two years later due to his radical ideas. His different approach toward architecture did not align with the ideas of [[Modernism (architecture)|modernism]] at the time. He wanted to create buildings responding to nature and the organic rhythm of life, which was unprecedented in the 1950s.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his third year of studies, he was told by the director of UBC that he had \"a wrong background\" for the program and the profession. After he left Vancouver and returned to Red Deer to start working at local architectural firms as a draftsman. His ejection from UBC made it impossible for him to apply to Canadian universities again. Cardinal himself also wanted a change of scenery due to racism towards Indigenous people in his home country so decided to head south, quickly stopping in Arizona and Mexico, and later settling in Texas.<ref name=\":1\" /> Eventually, he attended the [[University of Texas at Austin]], from which he graduated with a degree in Architecture in 1963.\n\nIn university, he also studied [[cultural anthropology]], due to his cultural heritage and philosophy based on the sacredness of life and nature. He wanted to study people and did not feel that the buildings around him were designed around people. His philosophy also intertwines with the philosophy of another famous architect, [[Rudolf Steiner|Rudolph Steiner]], whom Douglas studied at University of Texas. Steiner's work inspired Douglas to study [[anthropomorphism]], which he applied to his work as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> The idea of anthropomorphism and its concept of responding to the human behavior, natural cycle of life and beauty of sacred land and tectonics aligned with Cardinal's philosophy and his cultural heritage. Another great inspiration for Cardinal were works of [[Frank Lloyd Wright]]. He appreciated his organic way of responding to the landscape with the use of natural materials, such as stone and brick.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=17}}</ref> In Texas, he accepted his Indigenous heritage and one of his professors even encouraged him to learn more about his background.\n\n==Career==\nCardinal opened his private practice in 1964, and the same year he was commissioned to design St. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta.<ref>https://www.stmarysparishreddeer.com/parish/history/</ref> Construction was completed in 1968, and it has since been recognized as a prominent example in the history of Canadian architecture. In 2007, the church was featured on a [[Canada Post]] stamp series featuring four Canadian architects to commemorate the centennial of the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] (RAIC).<ref>https://postagestampguide.com/stamps/17713/st-mary-s-church-2007-canada-postage-stamp-royal-architectural-institute-of-canada-100-years</ref>\n\nBeginning with his work on St. Mary's, Cardinal was one of the first North American architects to use computers to assist in the design process. His curvilinear designs reflect the landscape around them, so that people making use of the building can retain a sense of the surrounding land. He found that the use of computerized design would fit best for his unusual designs and the use of shapes. He also found 3D programs very useful for laying out the exact dimensions of buildings.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=44}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, he was hired by the [[Smithsonian Institution]] as the Primary Design Architect for the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] (NMAI). The NMAI is currently situated on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], and is directly across from the [[United States Capitol|Capitol of the United States of America]]. After contractual disputes, Cardinal was removed from the project in 1998 before it was completed, but he continued to provide input into the building's design.\n\nIn 2008, his firm was hired by the Kirkland Foundation to design a museum/convention center in Union City, Tenn.  The [[Discovery Park of America]] was to be a unique structure housing a multi level museum with artifacts from across the nation as well as provide a place for large conventions/meetings for the community.  Early in 2009 the firm's contract was terminated with the owner, and all construction activity was halted, due to undisclosed differences between the two parties.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Douglas Cardinal.jpg|thumb|193x193px|Douglas Cardinal in 1970s]] -->\n\n=== Architectural Style and Philosophy ===\nThroughout his early years, Douglas Cardinal was dealing with racism and societal ideas of conformity for both his lifestyle and architecture. Only in his years in Texas he started to fully embrace his indigenous heritage and learn more about it.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=26}}</ref> In 1970s Cardinal developed his trademark architectural style with organic curvilinear forms. In those years he started wearing native clothes and necklaces, as well as becoming an advocate for indigenous rights.<ref name=\":2\" /> This spiritual connection with his native culture affected and influenced his work and unique architectural approach. Many philosophical ideas of indigenous history include its respect and sensibility towards nature, humans' inseparable relationship with the environment and land. These concepts resulted in his use of natural materials, organic shapes, soil and sun studies, as well as creating spaces that move people spiritually and make them appreciative of their surroundings. The native philosophy is also very contrasting from the Western civilization worldview due to its use of time. It is appreciative of resilience of nature and its ability to withstand hard conditions. Therefore, its architecture aims to last for seven generations, as opposed to the economically driven and efficient approach of the patriachial society.<ref name=\":0\" />\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:St. Mary's Church, Red Deer, Alberta.jpg|left|thumb|Cardinal's first building - St. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta]] -->\n\n=== St. Mary's Church ===\nSt. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta is Cardinal's first building. Upon his return to Alberta, Cardinal met with Father Werner Merx, who wanted the new church be innovative and unique. The archbishop of the church has already appointed another architect for the job, but Merx insisted on hiring Cardinal and realizing his vision. The archbishop whom they needed to convince turned out to be Anthony Jordan, who helped to resolve legal case for Cardinal 10 years earlier. Douglas Cardinal was approved for a job.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=22}}</ref>\n\nThe church has 750 seats inside and includes tubular skylights for natural daylight. Cardinal started his first project in 1967 and it turned out to be so challenging that he doubted if he could survive its completion. However, the building became one of his iconic designs that determined his architectural style. He combined all of his philosophical and cultural ideas and created a church that represented his many beliefs towards the nature and organic forms, that is unique and unprecedented for its time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=24}}</ref>\n\n=== Canadian Museum of History ===\n[[File:Gatineau - QC - Museum of Civilisation2.jpg|thumb|Canadian Museum of History|alt=]]This building, opened in 1989 as Canadian Museum of Civilization at the time, is another project that is very representative of Cardinal's architectural style. Influenced by his indigenous heritage it focuses on the response to its surroundings. It is located on the banks of the Ottawa River, facing [[Parliament Hill]]. All the massive government buildings in the city center are clustered and turned away from the river. Cardinal opened the Great Hall towards the river, making it the only building in the area that is responding to it. This approach also translated into the wrapping facade with curves that can embrace and invite people inside and create welcoming environment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=28}}</ref> The envelope of the building is shaped in an organic form, as if sculptured by the forces of nature. He also wanted to acknowledge his appreciation for the Parliament by using the same limestone as the one used in the building. Besides responding to the site conditions, the museum also engages with its historic context by including totem poles and native murals inside the building.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=29}}</ref> He wanted the space inside feel alive and dynamic, and not limit its form to the programmatic requirements.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=34}}</ref> Former Canadian prime minister Pierre Trudeau also encouraged Cardinal to create a museum where people embrace their different backgrounds and learn from each other. Prime minister's idea for multicultural Canadian society aligned well with Cardinal's vision.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=31}}</ref> The overall concept and purpose of the building corresponded with his ideas. However, in 1984 new government was not approving of Cardinal's design. He then lost his team on the project and was not fully paid for his previous work. This was a tremendous loss for the architect, but he was too driven to fulfill this project and was not willing to give up. After long years of defending his design, he eventually finished the museum and it became on of his many fundamental projects.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=33}}</ref>\n\n=== The Group of Seven ===\nIn 20th century, there were several artistic hierarchies, such as [[Group of Seven (artists)|Canadian Group of Seven]]. Cardinal was part of a similar group that included some of Canada's most influential architects, such as [[Moshe Safdie]], [[Raymond Moriyama]], [[Eberhard Zeidler]], [[Arthur Erickson]], [[Ray Affleck]] and Ron Thom. This environment was encouraging for the architect and they often shared ideas and passion to create great architecture.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=36}}</ref> Although all of their styles and conceptual vision were different, they all agreed on creating with meaning and beauty, instead of commercial skyscrapers of that era. However, his personal and financial problems often made him lose his direction and consequently he did not receive as much recognition as his peers.<ref name=\":3\" /> These instances include his design of the Grand Prairie Regional College in Alberta. Opened in 1974, this project did not meet government's simplistic and modernistic vision for the project and went over budget.\n\n==Works==\nAmong the many projects Cardinal has completed in his career are the following:<ref name=Doyle>{{cite book|last=Doyle|first=Richard I.|title=Renaissance II: Canadian creativity and innovation in the new millennium|year=2001|publisher=Intercept Ltd|isbn=978-0-660-18397-8|pages=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WrhJnmXdBIC&pg=PA38&dq=Douglas+Cardinal#v=onepage&q=Douglas%20Cardinal&f=false}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nSpruce Grove City Hall.jpg|Spruce Grove City Hall (1981) in [[Spruce Grove]], [[Alberta]]\nSpace-and-Science-Centre-Edmonton-Alberta.jpg|[[Edmonton Space and Science Centre|Edmonton Space And Science Centre]] (1984) Coronation Park, [[Edmonton, Alberta]], which has since been renovated and rebranded as the [[Telus World of Science]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\nGatineau - QC - Museum of Civilisation3.jpg|[[Canadian Museum of History]] (1989) in [[Gatineau, Quebec]], opposite [[Parliament Hill]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\nYork Region Administrative Centre 02.jpg|[[York Regional Council#York Region Administrative Centre|York Region Administrative Centre]] (1992) in [[Newmarket, Ontario]]\nNational Museum of the American Indian.JPG|[[Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of the American Indian]] (1993\u20131998) [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\">{{cite book |title='Fitzhenry and Whiteside Book of Canadian Facts and Dates'  |last=Pound |first=Richard W. |publisher=Fitzhenry and Whiteside |year=2005}}</ref>\nOuj\u00e9-Bougoumou.jpg|Cultural Institute (1996) [[Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou, Qu\u00e9bec]]\nFirst Nations University 4.jpg|[[First Nations University of Canada|First Nations University]] (2003) in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]]\nGordon Oakes Red Bear Centre.jpg|Gordon Oakes Red Bear Centre (2016) at the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]]\n</gallery>\n* St. Mary's Church (1968) [[Red Deer, Alberta]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\n* St. Albert Place & City Hall (1976) [[St. Albert, Alberta]]\n* Alberta Government Services (Provincial) Building (1976) [[Ponoka, Alberta]]\n* [[Grande Prairie Regional College]] (1976) [[Grande Prairie]], [[Alberta]]\n* Leighton Artist Colony, at the Banff Centre (1985) [[Banff, Alberta]]\n*Wabano Centre (2013) [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Grotski Residence (1978) [[Edmonton|Edmonton, Alberta]]\n*Bonneville Rehabilitation Centre [[Bonnyville|Bonnyville, Alberta]]\n*Ojigkwanong Students Centre, Carleton University, [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Ile a la Crosse Elementary School [[\u00cele-\u00e0-la-Crosse|\u00cele-\u00e0-la-Crosse, Saskatchewan]]\n*Cardinal Studio [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury, Ontario]]\n*Ouje' Bougoumou Village, [[Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou|Ouje' Bougoumou, Quebec]]\n*Janvier Gallery [[Cold Lake, Alberta]]\n*Grand Traverse Civic Centre Ottawa, Ontario\n*Circle of Life Thunderbird Place (2001) [[Winnipeg|Winnipeg, Manitoba]]\n*Jehovah's Witnesses Kingdom Hall (1991) [[Gatineau|Gatineau, Quebec]]\n*Kanai Middle School (1996) Sioux Valley, Manitoba\n*Iskotew Healing Lodge [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Sioux Valley (1986) Sioux Valley, Manitoba\n*Cardinal Residence (1982) [[Stony Plain, Alberta]]\n*Fairview Elementary School (1975) [[Red Deer, Alberta]]\n*Precam Elementary School (1976) La Ronge, Edmonton\n*Long Point First Nation, [[Winneway|Winneway,\u00a0Quebec]]\n*Me-No-Ya Win Health Centre (2010) [[Sioux Lookout|Sioux lookout, Ontario]]\n*Adelante Healthcare Goodyear Project (2018) [[Mesa, Arizona]]\n*Gordon Oakes Redbear Students Centre (2016) [[Saskatoon|Saskatoon, Saskatchewan]]\n*Unceded: Voices of the Land Exhibition (2018) [[Venice Biennale]]\n\n== Achievements ==\n\n=== Writings ===\n\n* ''Of the Spirit,'' NeWest Press (Edmonton, Alberta, Canada), 1977.<ref name=\":4\">Douglas Joseph Cardinal. ''Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors'', Gale, 2016. ''Gale Literature Resource Center''</ref>\n* (With Trevor Boddy) ''The Architecture of Douglas Cardinal,'' NeWest Press (Edmonton, Alberta, Canada), 1989.<ref name=\":4\" />\n* (With Jeanette C. Armstrong) ''The Native Creative Process,'' Theytus Books, 1994.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Awards ===\nIn 2005 Cardinal was awarded The Distinguished Artist Award from the [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] for \u201ccreating an indigenous style of Canadian architecture, characterized by gracious organic forms, which continually challenged the most advanced engineering standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsawards.ca/distinguished-artists/2005-douglas-cardinal/|title=2005 - Douglas Cardinal  2005 \u2013 Douglas Cardinal|publisher=Lieutenang Governor of Alberta Arts Awards|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n* Honor award, Alberta Association of Architects, 1968;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Honor award, City of Red Deer, Alberta, 1969;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Award of Excellence, City of Red Deer, Alberta, 1978;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Award of Excellence, ''Canadian Architect,'' 1972;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Member, Royal Canadian Academy of Arts, 1974;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Achievement of Excellence Award in Architecture, Province of Alberta, 1974;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Fellow, Royal Architectural Institute of Canada, 1983;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Banff Centre National Arts Award, 1990;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Canada Council Molson Prize for the Arts, 1993;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Aboriginal Achievement Award, 1995;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* RAIC Gold Medal for Architectural Achievement, 1999;<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.djcarchitect.com/awards|title=Douglas Cardinal Architect. Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Royal Architectural Institute of Canada, Millennium Celebration of Architecture, St. Mary\u2019s Church, Alberta, 2000;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Juan Torres Higueras Award, Federation of Pan American Associations of Architects, 2000;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Governor General\u2019s Award in Visual and Media Arts, Ottawa, Ontario, 2001;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Best Building Award, Grand Traverse Centre, United Contractor of America, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* United Nations Award for Sustainable Design, Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou Village, Quebec, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Golden Jubilee Medal in honor of Her Majesty The Queen\u2019s 50th Anniversary, Ottawa, Ontario, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* \u201cDouglas J. Cardinal Performing Arts Centre\u201d opens in GRPC, Grand Prairie, Alberta, 2004;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Laureate, Canada Council of the Arts, 2004;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Presidential Award, Masonry Design Awards, First Nations University, 2005;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Lieutenant Governor of Alberta Excellence in the Arts Award, Banff, Alberta, 2005;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Outstanding Professional Achievement Award, American Society of Landscape Architects, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* \u201cWorld Master of Contemporary Architecture\u201d by the IAA, Sofia, Bulgaria, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Outstanding Professional Achievement Award, American Society of Landscape Architects, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Canada Post postage stamp - Douglas Cardinal and St. Mary's Church - commemorating RAIC's 100th Anniversary, 2007;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* IAA Grand Prix Crystal Globe, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* St. Albert Place and City Hall declared \u2018Municipal Historic Resource\u2019, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Gold Medal of the Union of Architects of Russia, Moscow, Russia, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Best Public Services Development in Canada Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, International Property Awards, Essex, United Kingdom, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Alberta Masonry Design \u201cLifetime Achievement\u201d Award, 2010;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Wood WORKS! \u201cNorthern Ontario Excellence\u201d Award for Sioux Lookout Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, 2011;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Ontario Wood Works \u201cNorthern Ontario Excellence Award\u201d for Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, 2012;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* RAIC-NSAA Le Prix du XXe si\u00e8cle for Grand Prairie Regional College, 2013;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Presidential Award from the Saskatchewan Masonry Institute for Gordon Oaks Red Bear Student Center in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, 2016;<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nAfter his return to Red Deer, Douglas Cardinal met his former high school sweetheart Deirdre. Her Irish Catholic family did not accept of their relationship because of his heritage and the two of them eloped. This also was a problem, because Cardinal had charges pressed against him as an interracial marriage was illegal at the time. He was defended by the archbishop lawyer Anthony Jordan and was not found guilty. Deirdre then was pressured to move back with her family, and was raising their first daughter alone.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nShortly before he decided to go the Unites States, he started a relationship with Carole Olson. She accompanied him on a road trip 1957 to Texas and they later got married. They had three children - Nancy, Guy and Bret. The couple split during their years in America due to his preoccupation with work.<ref name=\":7\" /> His son Bret is also an architect and has worked with his father for 25 years until he started his own architecture firm.\n\nHe married Marylin Zahar in 1973, with whom he had two children - Lisa and Jean-Marc.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nHis current wife Idoia Arana-Beobide is also of Basque indigenous heritage. Together they have two children.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=46}}</ref> His wife works as a director at his architectural firm.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Commons}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\nHall, J. (July 14, 2014). ''The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots.'' Toronto, ON: Toronto Newspapers Limited. {{ISBN|9780887858017}}.\n\nDouglas Cardinal. (2018). ''The Canadian Architect, 63''(2), 30\u201332.\n\n''Douglas Joseph Cardinal.'' (2016). Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors, Gale. Gale Literature Resource Center.\n\nCardinal, D. J. (1998). ''Architecture as a living process.'' Canadian Journal of Native Education, ''22''(1), 3.\n\nLiscombe, R. \u00a0(2003). ''Cardinal, Douglas.'' Grove Art Online. Retrieved on 2020-03-30 from https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000014003.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.djcarchitect.com/ Architect's web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706171452/http://canadacouncil.ca/canadacouncil/archives/prizes/ggvma/2001/2001-01-e.asp Canada Council 2001 Governor General's Award for Visual and Media Arts]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A27598-2004Sep16.html Washington Post]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110814092508/http://dcardinalproject.tumblr.com/ Douglas Cardinal Archiving Project]\n*[https://www.historymuseum.ca/cmc/exhibitions/cmc/architecture/tour09e.html History Museum of Canada]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cardinal, Douglas}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Blackfoot people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of M\u00e9tis descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian architects]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Expressionist architects]]\n[[Category:First Nations artists]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Award in Visual and Media Arts winners]]\n[[Category:Indigenous architecture]]\n[[Category:Indspire Awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox architect\n|name                 = Douglas Cardinal\n|image                = Douglas Cardinal - 2016 (25010970829).jpg\n|caption              = Cardinal in 2016\n|nationality          = \n|birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1934|3|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place          = [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n|death_date           = \n|death_place          = \n|alma_mater           =[[University of British Columbia]]; [[University of Texas at Austin]], \n|practice             = \n|significant_buildings= \n|significant_projects = [[National Museum of the American Indian]]; [[Grande Prairie Regional College]]; [[Canadian Museum of History]]; \n|significant_design   = \n|awards               = \n}}\n'''Douglas Joseph Cardinal''', [[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada|FRAIC]] (born 7 March 1934) is an [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Indigenous]] [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[architect]] based in [[Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada. His flowing architecture marked with smooth curvilinear forms is influenced by his [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] heritage as well as European [[Expressionist architecture]].<ref name=\"CE\">[http://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-joseph-cardinal/ Douglas Cardinal], The Canadian Encyclopedia</ref> His passion for unconventional forms and appreciation of nature and landscape were present in his life from a very young age, and consequently developed into the unique architectural style he has employed throughout his career. Cardinal is perhaps best known for his designs of the [[Canadian Museum of History]] in [[Gatineau, Quebec]] (1989) and the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] (1998).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=39}}</ref> He is considered one of the most influential Aboriginal architects, having shaped and preserved indigenous architecture and culture in modern history.\n\n==Life==\nBorn in [[Calgary, Alberta]] to parents Joseph and Frances Cardinal, Douglas Cardinal is the eldest of eight children. His father was of [[Blackfoot]]/Kainai and Algonquin heritage, and his mother was of German and [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] descent.<ref name=\"CE\"/> His mother worked as a nurse and was very well educated. Cardinal's parents met in 1926, and in the first half of the 20th century women had very little status and rights. The patriarchal society did not recognize educated women like Frances Cardinal. However, his father's tribe's societal norms accepted a matrilineal culture, where women are very respected and admired.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 2018|title=Douglas Cardinal|url=|journal=The Canadian Architect|volume= 63, Iss. 2|pages=30\u201332|via=}}</ref> These cultural ideas shaped Cardinal's upbringing and affected his worldview and relationship with his heritage. He has recalled that his mother told him at a young age, \u201cYou\u2019re going to be an architect.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n \nCardinal grew up in a small city in [[Red Deer, Alberta]]. He was sent to St. Joseph's Convent Catholic [[Canadian Indian residential school system|Residential School]] and spent the remainder of his high school years in Red Deer. [[Grey Nuns]] taught him about arts and culture, and he has said that his religious school influenced him immensely. Living away from the rest of his family made him focus on his academic achievements. Traditional sacred architecture and its role in culture made him want to create spaces as powerful and inspirational as churches and basilicas. It also ignited in him a passion for architecture in those early years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, Ontario|pages=14}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, he started studying architecture at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) but was forced to leave two years later due to his radical ideas. His different approach toward architecture did not align with the ideas of [[Modernism (architecture)|modernism]] at the time. He wanted to create buildings responding to nature and the organic rhythm of life, which was unprecedented in the 1950s.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his third year of studies, he was told by the director of UBC that he had \"a wrong background\" for the program and the profession. After he left Vancouver and returned to Red Deer to start working at local architectural firms as a draftsman. His ejection from UBC made it impossible for him to apply to Canadian universities again. Cardinal himself also wanted a change of scenery due to racism towards Indigenous people in his home country so decided to head south, quickly stopping in Arizona and Mexico, and later settling in Texas.<ref name=\":1\" /> Eventually, he attended the [[University of Texas at Austin]], from which he graduated with a degree in Architecture in 1963.\n\nIn university, he also studied [[cultural anthropology]], due to his cultural heritage and philosophy based on the sacredness of life and nature. He wanted to study people and did not feel that the buildings around him were designed around people. His philosophy also intertwines with the philosophy of another famous architect, [[Rudolf Steiner|Rudolph Steiner]], whom Douglas studied at University of Texas. Steiner's work inspired Douglas to study [[anthropomorphism]], which he applied to his work as well.<ref name=\":0\" /> The idea of anthropomorphism and its concept of responding to the human behavior, natural cycle of life and beauty of sacred land and tectonics aligned with Cardinal's philosophy and his cultural heritage. Another great inspiration for Cardinal were works of [[Frank Lloyd Wright]]. He appreciated his organic way of responding to the landscape with the use of natural materials, such as stone and brick.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=17}}</ref> In Texas, he accepted his Indigenous heritage and one of his professors even encouraged him to learn more about his background.\n\n==Career==\nCardinal opened his private practice in 1964, and the same year he was commissioned to design St. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta.<ref>https://www.stmarysparishreddeer.com/parish/history/</ref> Construction was completed in 1968, and it has since been recognized as a prominent example in the history of Canadian architecture. In 2007, the church was featured on a [[Canada Post]] stamp series featuring four Canadian architects to commemorate the centennial of the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada]] (RAIC).<ref>https://postagestampguide.com/stamps/17713/st-mary-s-church-2007-canada-postage-stamp-royal-architectural-institute-of-canada-100-years</ref>\n\nBeginning with his work on St. Mary's, Cardinal was one of the first North American architects to use computers to assist in the design process. His curvilinear designs reflect the landscape around them, so that people making use of the building can retain a sense of the surrounding land. He found that the use of computerized design would fit best for his unusual designs and the use of shapes. He also found 3D programs very useful for laying out the exact dimensions of buildings.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=44}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, he was hired by the [[Smithsonian Institution]] as the Primary Design Architect for the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] (NMAI). The NMAI is currently situated on the [[National Mall]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], and is directly across from the [[United States Capitol|Capitol of the United States of America]]. After contractual disputes, Cardinal was removed from the project in 1998 before it was completed, but he continued to provide input into the building's design.\n\nIn 2008, his firm was hired by the Kirkland Foundation to design a museum/convention center in Union City, Tenn.  The [[Discovery Park of America]] was to be a unique structure housing a multi level museum with artifacts from across the nation as well as provide a place for large conventions/meetings for the community.  Early in 2009 the firm's contract was terminated with the owner, and all construction activity was halted, due to undisclosed differences between the two parties.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Douglas Cardinal.jpg|thumb|193x193px|Douglas Cardinal in 1970s]] -->\n\n=== Architectural Style and Philosophy ===\nThroughout his early years, Douglas Cardinal was dealing with racism and societal ideas of conformity for both his lifestyle and architecture. Only in his years in Texas he started to fully embrace his indigenous heritage and learn more about it.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=26}}</ref> In 1970s Cardinal developed his trademark architectural style with organic curvilinear forms. In those years he started wearing native clothes and necklaces, as well as becoming an advocate for indigenous rights.<ref name=\":2\" /> This spiritual connection with his native culture affected and influenced his work and unique architectural approach. Many philosophical ideas of indigenous history include its respect and sensibility towards nature, humans' inseparable relationship with the environment and land. These concepts resulted in his use of natural materials, organic shapes, soil and sun studies, as well as creating spaces that move people spiritually and make them appreciative of their surroundings. The native philosophy is also very contrasting from the Western civilization worldview due to its use of time. It is appreciative of resilience of nature and its ability to withstand hard conditions. Therefore, its architecture aims to last for seven generations, as opposed to the economically driven and efficient approach of the patriachial society.<ref name=\":0\" />\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:St. Mary's Church, Red Deer, Alberta.jpg|left|thumb|Cardinal's first building - St. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta]] -->\n\n=== St. Mary's Church ===\nSt. Mary's Church in Red Deer, Alberta is Cardinal's first building. Upon his return to Alberta, Cardinal met with Father Werner Merx, who wanted the new church be innovative and unique. The archbishop of the church has already appointed another architect for the job, but Merx insisted on hiring Cardinal and realizing his vision. The archbishop whom they needed to convince turned out to be Anthony Jordan, who helped to resolve legal case for Cardinal 10 years earlier. Douglas Cardinal was approved for a job.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=22}}</ref>\n\nThe church has 750 seats inside and includes tubular skylights for natural daylight. Cardinal started his first project in 1967 and it turned out to be so challenging that he doubted if he could survive its completion. However, the building became one of his iconic designs that determined his architectural style. He combined all of his philosophical and cultural ideas and created a church that represented his many beliefs towards the nature and organic forms, that is unique and unprecedented for its time.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=24}}</ref>\n\n=== Canadian Museum of History ===\n[[File:Gatineau - QC - Museum of Civilisation2.jpg|thumb|Canadian Museum of History|alt=]]This building, opened in 1989 as Canadian Museum of Civilization at the time, is another project that is very representative of Cardinal's architectural style. Influenced by his indigenous heritage it focuses on the response to its surroundings. It is located on the banks of the Ottawa River, facing [[Parliament Hill]]. All the massive government buildings in the city center are clustered and turned away from the river. Cardinal opened the Great Hall towards the river, making it the only building in the area that is responding to it. This approach also translated into the wrapping facade with curves that can embrace and invite people inside and create welcoming environment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=28}}</ref> The envelope of the building is shaped in an organic form, as if sculptured by the forces of nature. He also wanted to acknowledge his appreciation for the Parliament by using the same limestone as the one used in the building. Besides responding to the site conditions, the museum also engages with its historic context by including totem poles and native murals inside the building.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=29}}</ref> He wanted the space inside feel alive and dynamic, and not limit its form to the programmatic requirements.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=34}}</ref> Former Canadian prime minister Pierre Trudeau also encouraged Cardinal to create a museum where people embrace their different backgrounds and learn from each other. Prime minister's idea for multicultural Canadian society aligned well with Cardinal's vision.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=31}}</ref> The overall concept and purpose of the building corresponded with his ideas. However, in 1984 new government was not approving of Cardinal's design. He then lost his team on the project and was not fully paid for his previous work. This was a tremendous loss for the architect, but he was too driven to fulfill this project and was not willing to give up. After long years of defending his design, he eventually finished the museum and it became on of his many fundamental projects.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=33}}</ref>\n\n=== The Group of Seven ===\nIn 20th century, there were several artistic hierarchies, such as [[Group of Seven (artists)|Canadian Group of Seven]]. Cardinal was part of a similar group that included Greatest Canadian Postwar Architects, along with Moshe Safdie, Raymond Moriyama, Eberhard Zeidler, Arthur Erickson, Ray Affleck and Ron Thom. This environment was encouraging for the architect and they often shared ideas and passion to create great architecture.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=36}}</ref> Although all of their styles and conceptual vision were different, they all agreed on creating with meaning and beauty, instead of commercial skyscrapers of that era. However, his personal and financial problems often made him lose his direction and consequently he did not receive as much recognition as his peers.<ref name=\":3\" /> These instances include his design of the Grand Prairie Regional College in Alberta. Opened in 1974, this project did not meet government's simplistic and modernistic vision for the project and went over budget.\n\n==Works==\nAmong the many projects Cardinal has completed in his career are the following:<ref name=Doyle>{{cite book|last=Doyle|first=Richard I.|title=Renaissance II: Canadian creativity and innovation in the new millennium|year=2001|publisher=Intercept Ltd|isbn=978-0-660-18397-8|pages=38|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WrhJnmXdBIC&pg=PA38&dq=Douglas+Cardinal#v=onepage&q=Douglas%20Cardinal&f=false}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nSpruce Grove City Hall.jpg|Spruce Grove City Hall (1981) in [[Spruce Grove]], [[Alberta]]\nSpace-and-Science-Centre-Edmonton-Alberta.jpg|[[Edmonton Space and Science Centre|Edmonton Space And Science Centre]] (1984) Coronation Park, [[Edmonton, Alberta]], which has since been renovated and rebranded as the [[Telus World of Science]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\nGatineau - QC - Museum of Civilisation3.jpg|[[Canadian Museum of History]] (1989) in [[Gatineau, Quebec]], opposite [[Parliament Hill]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\nYork Region Administrative Centre 02.jpg|[[York Regional Council#York Region Administrative Centre|York Region Administrative Centre]] (1992) in [[Newmarket, Ontario]]\nNational Museum of the American Indian.JPG|[[Smithsonian]] [[National Museum of the American Indian]] (1993\u20131998) [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\">{{cite book |title='Fitzhenry and Whiteside Book of Canadian Facts and Dates'  |last=Pound |first=Richard W. |publisher=Fitzhenry and Whiteside |year=2005}}</ref>\nOuj\u00e9-Bougoumou.jpg|Cultural Institute (1996) [[Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou, Qu\u00e9bec]]\nFirst Nations University 4.jpg|[[First Nations University of Canada|First Nations University]] (2003) in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]]\nGordon Oakes Red Bear Centre.jpg|Gordon Oakes Red Bear Centre (2016) at the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]]\n</gallery>\n* St. Mary's Church (1968) [[Red Deer, Alberta]]<ref name=\"Pound 2005\"/>\n* St. Albert Place & City Hall (1976) [[St. Albert, Alberta]]\n* Alberta Government Services (Provincial) Building (1976) [[Ponoka, Alberta]]\n* [[Grande Prairie Regional College]] (1976) [[Grande Prairie]], [[Alberta]]\n* Leighton Artist Colony, at the Banff Centre (1985) [[Banff, Alberta]]\n*Wabano Centre (2013) [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Grotski Residence (1978) [[Edmonton|Edmonton, Alberta]]\n*Bonneville Rehabilitation Centre [[Bonnyville|Bonnyville, Alberta]]\n*Ojigkwanong Students Centre, Carleton University, [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Ile a la Crosse Elementary School [[\u00cele-\u00e0-la-Crosse|\u00cele-\u00e0-la-Crosse, Saskatchewan]]\n*Cardinal Studio [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury, Ontario]]\n*Ouje' Bougoumou Village, [[Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou|Ouje' Bougoumou, Quebec]]\n*Janvier Gallery [[Cold Lake, Alberta]]\n*Grand Traverse Civic Centre Ottawa, Ontario\n*Circle of Life Thunderbird Place (2001) [[Winnipeg|Winnipeg, Manitoba]]\n*Jehovah's Witnesses Kingdom Hall (1991) [[Gatineau|Gatineau, Quebec]]\n*Kanai Middle School (1996) Sioux Valley, Manitoba\n*Iskotew Healing Lodge [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]\n*Sioux Valley (1986) Sioux Valley, Manitoba\n*Cardinal Residence (1982) [[Stony Plain, Alberta]]\n*Fairview Elementary School (1975) [[Red Deer, Alberta]]\n*Precam Elementary School (1976) La Ronge, Edmonton\n*Long Point First Nation, [[Winneway|Winneway,\u00a0Quebec]]\n*Me-No-Ya Win Health Centre (2010) [[Sioux Lookout|Sioux lookout, Ontario]]\n*Adelante Healthcare Goodyear Project (2018) [[Mesa, Arizona]]\n*Gordon Oakes Redbear Students Centre (2016) [[Saskatoon|Saskatoon, Saskatchewan]]\n*Unceded: Voices of the Land Exhibition (2018) [[Venice Biennale]]\n\n== Achievements ==\n\n=== Writings ===\n\n* ''Of the Spirit,'' NeWest Press (Edmonton, Alberta, Canada), 1977.<ref name=\":4\">Douglas Joseph Cardinal. ''Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors'', Gale, 2016. ''Gale Literature Resource Center''</ref>\n* (With Trevor Boddy) ''The Architecture of Douglas Cardinal,'' NeWest Press (Edmonton, Alberta, Canada), 1989.<ref name=\":4\" />\n* (With Jeanette C. Armstrong) ''The Native Creative Process,'' Theytus Books, 1994.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Awards ===\nIn 2005 Cardinal was awarded The Distinguished Artist Award from the [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] for \u201ccreating an indigenous style of Canadian architecture, characterized by gracious organic forms, which continually challenged the most advanced engineering standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsawards.ca/distinguished-artists/2005-douglas-cardinal/|title=2005 - Douglas Cardinal  2005 \u2013 Douglas Cardinal|publisher=Lieutenang Governor of Alberta Arts Awards|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n* Honor award, Alberta Association of Architects, 1968;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Honor award, City of Red Deer, Alberta, 1969;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Award of Excellence, City of Red Deer, Alberta, 1978;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Award of Excellence, ''Canadian Architect,'' 1972;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Member, Royal Canadian Academy of Arts, 1974;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Achievement of Excellence Award in Architecture, Province of Alberta, 1974;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Fellow, Royal Architectural Institute of Canada, 1983;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Banff Centre National Arts Award, 1990;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Canada Council Molson Prize for the Arts, 1993;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* Aboriginal Achievement Award, 1995;<ref name=\":4\" />\n* RAIC Gold Medal for Architectural Achievement, 1999;<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.djcarchitect.com/awards|title=Douglas Cardinal Architect. Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Royal Architectural Institute of Canada, Millennium Celebration of Architecture, St. Mary\u2019s Church, Alberta, 2000;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Juan Torres Higueras Award, Federation of Pan American Associations of Architects, 2000;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Governor General\u2019s Award in Visual and Media Arts, Ottawa, Ontario, 2001;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Best Building Award, Grand Traverse Centre, United Contractor of America, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* United Nations Award for Sustainable Design, Ouj\u00e9-Bougoumou Village, Quebec, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Golden Jubilee Medal in honor of Her Majesty The Queen\u2019s 50th Anniversary, Ottawa, Ontario, 2002;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* \u201cDouglas J. Cardinal Performing Arts Centre\u201d opens in GRPC, Grand Prairie, Alberta, 2004;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Laureate, Canada Council of the Arts, 2004;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Presidential Award, Masonry Design Awards, First Nations University, 2005;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Lieutenant Governor of Alberta Excellence in the Arts Award, Banff, Alberta, 2005;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Outstanding Professional Achievement Award, American Society of Landscape Architects, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* \u201cWorld Master of Contemporary Architecture\u201d by the IAA, Sofia, Bulgaria, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Outstanding Professional Achievement Award, American Society of Landscape Architects, 2006;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Canada Post postage stamp - Douglas Cardinal and St. Mary's Church - commemorating RAIC's 100th Anniversary, 2007;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* IAA Grand Prix Crystal Globe, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* St. Albert Place and City Hall declared \u2018Municipal Historic Resource\u2019, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Gold Medal of the Union of Architects of Russia, Moscow, Russia, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Best Public Services Development in Canada Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, International Property Awards, Essex, United Kingdom, 2009;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Alberta Masonry Design \u201cLifetime Achievement\u201d Award, 2010;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Wood WORKS! \u201cNorthern Ontario Excellence\u201d Award for Sioux Lookout Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, 2011;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Ontario Wood Works \u201cNorthern Ontario Excellence Award\u201d for Meno-Ya-Win Health Centre, 2012;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* RAIC-NSAA Le Prix du XXe si\u00e8cle for Grand Prairie Regional College, 2013;<ref name=\":5\" />\n* Presidential Award from the Saskatchewan Masonry Institute for Gordon Oaks Red Bear Student Center in Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, 2016;<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nAfter his return to Red Deer, Douglas Cardinal met his former high school sweetheart Deirdre. Her Irish Catholic family did not accept of their relationship because of his heritage and the two of them eloped. This also was a problem, because Cardinal had charges pressed against him as an interracial marriage was illegal at the time. He was defended by the archbishop lawyer Anthony Jordan and was not found guilty. Deirdre then was pressured to move back with her family, and was raising their first daughter alone.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nShortly before he decided to go the Unites States, he started a relationship with Carole Olson. She accompanied him on a road trip 1957 to Texas and they later got married. They had three children - Nancy, Guy and Bret. The couple split during their years in America due to his preoccupation with work.<ref name=\":7\" /> His son Bret is also an architect and has worked with his father for 25 years until he started his own architecture firm.\n\nHe married Marylin Zahar in 1973, with whom he had two children - Lisa and Jean-Marc.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nHis current wife Idoia Arana-Beobide is also of Basque indigenous heritage. Together they have two children.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hall|first=Joseph|title=The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots|publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Limited|date=July 14, 2014|isbn=9780887858017|location=Toronto, ON|pages=46}}</ref> His wife works as a director at his architectural firm.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Commons}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\nHall, J. (July 14, 2014). ''The Outsider: How Douglas Cardinal Draws Genius from Native Roots.'' Toronto, ON: Toronto Newspapers Limited. {{ISBN|9780887858017}}.\n\nDouglas Cardinal. (2018). ''The Canadian Architect, 63''(2), 30\u201332.\n\n''Douglas Joseph Cardinal.'' (2016). Gale Literature: Contemporary Authors, Gale. Gale Literature Resource Center.\n\nCardinal, D. J. (1998). ''Architecture as a living process.'' Canadian Journal of Native Education, ''22''(1), 3.\n\nLiscombe, R. \u00a0(2003). ''Cardinal, Douglas.'' Grove Art Online. Retrieved on 2020-03-30 from https://www.oxfordartonline.com/groveart/view/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.001.0001/oao-9781884446054-e-7000014003.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.djcarchitect.com/ Architect's web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110706171452/http://canadacouncil.ca/canadacouncil/archives/prizes/ggvma/2001/2001-01-e.asp Canada Council 2001 Governor General's Award for Visual and Media Arts]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A27598-2004Sep16.html Washington Post]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110814092508/htt